This article is about a proclamation issued by President Donald J. Trump declaring September 4 to September 6, 2020, as National Days of Prayer and Remembrance. The proclamation pays tribute to the nearly 3,000 lives lost on September 11, 2001, and honors their memory. It highlights the bravery of first responders and passengers on United Flight 93 who fought against the terrorists. The article mentions the Survivor Tree at Ground Zero in New York City as a symbol of faith and national restoration. It emphasizes the strength and resilience of the nation in the face of tragedy and calls upon the people of the United States to observe these days with appropriate programs, ceremonies, and activities.